metadata.name: Sunset on Water #50
metadata.description:
Third iteration of my Sumi-e inspired pieces.

This time featuring a sun setting over the ocean, seen through bamboo sprouts and some birds up in the air.

Placement and size of the sun as well as light differences in its colouring are determined by the hash. The bamboo will be fairly evenly distributed across the width of the image, but the size, off-sprouts and leafs are also randomised and will create a unique image every time.

Everything is generated programmatically. Implemented in Vanilla Javascript.

metadata.name: Concrete #379
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021

metadata.name: Syzers #187
metadata.description:
Syzers is a generative synthesizer project with sounds altered by Tone JS.

···· On Tuesday, May 17, unsold editions will be burned ····

Visually it consists of 16 layers, in which more than 350 elements are combined randomly, generating synthesizers with unique environments and landscapes.
As for the sound, 40 tracks were recorded with analog synthesizers that were then assigned to each of the modules. These, combined in groups of 4, provide thousands of possible combinations. 
In addition, these sounds will be further modified by code effects that will randomly vary their properties.

Click to listen to the sounds

Many thanks to @Jpupper and @Fipiaggio for help with programming the sound part and @Purespider for the template.

metadata.name: Paesaggio #37
metadata.description:
In this work I used the tools I learned in developing precedent works to generate a landscape with hills, flowers, streams, ruins, sky and clouds. The generated landscape gives the impression of a natural one but at the same time it has some "abstract" traits that reveal the geometrical properties of the noise generation process. This noise is used both for the morphological aspect and for colors assignment.

Developed with p5.js using WEBGL renderer.
Rendering is faster with chrome browser.

[s] to save a 1600x1600 png.


Features:
"Palette": 12 colormap
"Sky":  Day, Night, Gray - 15% Gray, 20% Night, 65% Day
"Ruins": True, False - 33% True
"Streams": True, False - 33% True
"Flower": Red-Blue, Fuchsia-Yellow, Rose-Violet
"Border": True, False - 25% True

Two meandering paths are created with opposite flow vectors. The paths are drawn with a twisty drip brush.

metadata.name: Making Mole Hills #180
metadata.description:
Making Mole Hills is a space filling algorithm, similar to a flood fill. Rules have been structured to create mountain shapes, rather than evenly filling the canvas. Seed pixels begin to propagate themselves outwards, based initial conditions. After the space has been filled, the algorithm will pause, and then new mountain building will commence.

Features:
- Pixel Detail: Low 60%, Medium 30%, or High 10%. Controls the resolution of the grid
- Color Mode: Multi-hued 85%, Duotone 10%, or Black and White 5%. Multihued palettes change slowly over time. If you aren't happy at first, wait a few minutes and it will evolve
- Avalanche: Can be either None 80%, Falling 15%, or Rising 5%. This controls color animation separate from the pixel expansion
- Peak Type: Crowded 50%, Clustered 25%, Coupled 17.5%, or Lonely 7.5%. # of seed pixels to start with
- Organization: Tumbled 50%, Chaotic 40%, Ordered 10%. Controls the amount of randomness as the piece expands
- Color Frequency: Variegated 50%, Soft 40%, Hyper 10%

metadata.name: Tesseract #178
metadata.description:
'Tesseract' is a generative collection drawing on the concept of the cube from oneirology, the interpretation of dreams. In many mythologies and fields of study, the square is considered a 'perfect shape', thus with its abstraction into three isometric dimensions, the cube is seen by some as a representation of the various aspects of the human condition.

In 'Tesseract', the ribbons flowing between the cubes represent the shared experiences that connect us all. No matter how different our lives might be, we all go through the same joys, sorrows, trials, tribulations and experience attachments of varying degrees. 

It is these experiences that bind us together and make us who we are. With these concepts in mind, viewers are invited to interpret each composition as it relates to them and their unique story, from the perspective of that which has been and that which is yet to be experienced.

Press 'S' to save a high resolution PNG at 2400 x 3396 px.
